comment.body:
I believe it was confusing in the code as it landed originally. It appears that the semantics of the drop guard were diametrically opposite for textures versus instances. Look at this description, for example:
```
    /// - If `drop_guard` is [`None`], wgpu-hal will take ownership of the texture. If `drop_guard` is
    ///   [`Some`], the texture must be valid until the drop implementation
    ///   of the drop guard is called.
```
It's the opposite of what Instance docs and code are saying. It was just confusing and wrong. The new flag `externally_owned` is unambiguous.

issue.body:
"a % b" expression gets passed through form WGSL to GLSL, e.g.
```rust
@vertex
fn main() -> @builtin(position) vec4<f32> {
	let x: i32 = -4 % 5;
	return vec4<f32>(0.0);
}
```
Produces:
```cpp
#version 310 es

precision highp float;
precision highp int;


void main() {
    int x = (-4 % 5);
    gl_Position = vec4(0.0);
    gl_Position.yz = vec2(-gl_Position.y, gl_Position.z * 2.0 - gl_Position.w);
    return;
}
```

Problem is - the semantics of "%" is different. In GLSL it's "x - y * floor(x/y)", while in WGSL it's meant to be "x - y * trunc(x/y)".

Example:
```rust
fn foo(a: vec3<bool>) -> vec3<bool> {
	return a || vec3<bool>(true, false, false);
}

@vertex
fn main() -> @builtin(position) vec4<f32> {
	return vec4<f32>(0.0);
}
```

Produced GLSL:
```cpp
#version 310 es

precision highp float;
precision highp int;


bvec3 foo(bvec3 a) {
    return (a || bvec3(true, false, false));
}

void main() {
    gl_Position = vec4(0.0);
    gl_Position.yz = vec2(-gl_Position.y, gl_Position.z * 2.0 - gl_Position.w);
    return;
}
```

This isn't a valid GLSL:
> ERROR: 0:8: '||' :  wrong operand types: no operation '||' exists that takes a left-hand operand of type ' in 3-component vector of bool' and a right operand of type ' const 3-component vector of bool' (or there is no acceptable conversion)
ERROR: 0:8: '' : compilation terminated

